{"title_page": "Cheryl Wall", "text_new": "'''Cheryl A. Wall''' (1948-2020) was a [[literary criticism|literary critic]] and professor of [[English studies|English]] at [[Rutgers University]]. She specializes in black women's writing, particularly the [[Harlem Renaissance]] and [[Zora Neale Hurston]]. She has edited several volumes of Hurston's writings for the Library of America. She is also a section editor for ''[[The Norton Anthology of African American Literature]]'' and is on the editorial board of ''[[American Literature (journal)|American Literature]]'', ''[[African American Review]]'' and ''[[Signs (journal)|Signs]]''.\n\nWall received her [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] from [[Howard University]] and her [[Ph.D]] from [[Harvard]]. An award-winning researcher and teacher, she was named the Board of Governors Zora Neale Hurston Professor in 2007.\n\nCheryl Wall has had a lifelong commitment to African-American arts and culture and was the founding board chair of the [[Crossroads Theatre|Crossroads Theater Company]], the first Black Theater in New Jersey, founded by two Rutgers graduates, Ricardo Khan and Lee Richardson in 1978.\n\n==Selected publications==\n* ''Changing Our Own Words: Criticism, Theory and Writing by Black Women'' (ed., 1989)\n* ''Women of the Harlem Renaissance'' (1995)\n* ''\"Sweat\": Texts and Contexts'' (ed., 1997)\n* ''[[Their Eyes Were Watching God]]: A Casebook'' (ed., 2000)\n* ''Worrying the Line: Black Women Writers, Lineage and Literary Tradition'' (2005)\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081007142511/http://english.rutgers.edu/faculty/profiles/wall.html Official web page]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wall, Cheryl}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American academics of English literature]]\n[[Category:American literary critics]]\n[[Category:Rutgers University faculty]]\n[[Category:Howard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n\n\n{{US-English-academic-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Cheryl A. Wall''' was a [[literary criticism|literary critic]] and professor of [[English studies|English]] at [[Rutgers University]]. She specializes in black women's writing, particularly the [[Harlem Renaissance]] and [[Zora Neale Hurston]]. She has edited several volumes of Hurston's writings for the Library of America. She is also a section editor for ''[[The Norton Anthology of African American Literature]]'' and is on the editorial board of ''[[American Literature (journal)|American Literature]]'', ''[[African American Review]]'' and ''[[Signs (journal)|Signs]]''.\n\nWall received her [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] from [[Howard University]] and her [[Ph.D]] from [[Harvard]]. An award-winning researcher and teacher, she was named the Board of Governors Zora Neale Hurston Professor in 2007.\n\nCheryl Wall has had a lifelong commitment to African-American arts and culture and was the founding board chair of the [[Crossroads Theatre|Crossroads Theater Company]], the first Black Theater in New Jersey, founded by two Rutgers graduates, Ricardo Khan and Lee Richardson in 1978.\n\n==Selected publications==\n* ''Changing Our Own Words: Criticism, Theory and Writing by Black Women'' (ed., 1989)\n* ''Women of the Harlem Renaissance'' (1995)\n* ''\"Sweat\": Texts and Contexts'' (ed., 1997)\n* ''[[Their Eyes Were Watching God]]: A Casebook'' (ed., 2000)\n* ''Worrying the Line: Black Women Writers, Lineage and Literary Tradition'' (2005)\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081007142511/http://english.rutgers.edu/faculty/profiles/wall.html Official web page]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wall, Cheryl}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American academics of English literature]]\n[[Category:American literary critics]]\n[[Category:Rutgers University faculty]]\n[[Category:Howard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alu